# Home Virtual Lab Setup

## Project Overview
Home Virtual Lab is a place where you can learn and practice different Opeararing Systems like Windows, MacOS and Linux.
User can learn and manage different process of an os like File Management, Networking, Process and Command Line Interface in an Isolated Sandbox Environment.

  ## Tools Needed
     - VMware Workstation (Host)
     - Kali Linux (Guest)

## FOLLOW THE SEQUENCE
Phase 1: Build the Virtual Machines
        - Download VMware Workstation Pro
           - Go to Broadcom Official Website and Signup
           - Navigate to Downloads and Scroll to download workstation pro
        - Download Kali Linux ISO
          - Go to Kali's Official Website
          - Choose Platform as Installer Images
          - Then download Installer Images ISO

Phase 2: Configuring Hypervisor
         - Create a new Virtual Machine
         - Custom (Advanced)
         - Choose Workstation H25 or later
         - Browser the ISO Image (Kali Linux) from Downloads
         - Choose Guest Operating System Type - Kali Linux version Debian 13x Debianx64
         - Give a Name to your Virtual Machine - Kali
         - Allocate the processors and cores per proccessor - Allocate atleast 4 processor cores for smoooth experience
         - Allocate Memory for your VM (Guest Machine) - Allocaat at lest 4GB RAM
         - Use Network Address Translation (NAT) default
         - I/O Controller Type - LSI Logic (Recommended)
         - Select a Disk Type - Choose Recommended by default
         - Create a new virtual disk
         - Split the disk and allocate atleast 35GB Space
         - Review Everything once before creating. If want to modify you can do

Phase 3: Starting up Virtual Machine
         - Choose Graphical Install
         - Chooose a System Languge, Location and Keyboard Language
         - Configure the network and enter hostname - kali or your preferred
         - If you have a domain name you enter or else just leave it by moving next step
         - Enter the user name and confirm password
         - Choose the Disk for partion - Recommended to use Entire Disk and keep all files in one partition then prompt for finish partioning the disk
         - Then the system will Install Automatically
         - Choose gdm3 as default display manager
         - Install GRUB Load on the disk choose the disk and prompt for yes
         - You need to choose Kali Linux Interface like Xfce, GNOME, KDE Plasma - Recommended Xfce by default
          Note: You can change your interface later by installing the required interface in terminal
         - Finsh the Installation - Reboot the system
         - Login with user name and password - The New Virtual Operating System is yours
         Note: Update the system in terminal
                1. Sudo apt update
                2. Sudo apt upgrade -y
                3. Sudo apt autoremove -y
            Enjoy your new Operating System
